                    <note xml:lang="en" type="abstract" corresp="http://syriaca.org/persons http://syriaca.org/q http://syriaca.org/saints">
                        <quote source="#bib370-1">Monk and abbot. Barṣawmo was a supporter of
                                <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/2432">Dioscorus of
                                Alexandria</persName>.</quote>
                    </note>
                    <note xml:lang="en" type="description" resp="http://syriaca.org">In early sources, <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/370">Barsauma</persName> was known for
                        his ardent support for <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/2432">Dioscorus of Alexandria</persName> at the Second Council of <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/623">Ephesus</placeName> and his support
                        for <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/482">Eutyches</persName> at the
                        Council of <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/622">Chalcedon</placeName>. In later hagiography, <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/370">Barsauma</persName> was widely
                        commemorated in the miaphysite churches as a monastic and missionary leader
                        who was the head of mourners at a monastery near <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/136">Melitene</placeName>. A later
                        influential Syrian orthodox monastery in the same region, <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/224">Dayro d-Mor Barṣawmo</placeName>, was
                        named after him. He was a disciple of <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/1109">Abraham of the high
                            mountain</persName>.</note>
                    <note xml:lang="en" type="discursive" source="#bib370-8">See the Life of
                        Barsaum, with his 99 or 100 miracles, written in about 550-61.</note>
